  "cover_link": "https://static.wikia.nocookie.net/marveldatabase/images/c/c7/Amazing_Spider-Man_Vol_1_2.jpg",
  "plot_summary": "A new villain called the Vulture swoops out of the sky to steal things, and Jameson, editor of Now Magazine prepares to devote the next issue to the Vulture (with Spider-Man also featured, as always of course).&nbsp; Jameson wants photos, but no one can get close enough to the Vulture to get them!\n\nWhen Peter Parker hears about the magazine wanting photos, he realizes immediately that <i>he</i> could get them!&nbsp; After school, Aunt May gives him one of Ben's old cameras, and he dons his costume to go out and get photos of the Vulture, pausing only long enough to work out how to attach the camera to his costume so that he is free to use his hands.\n\nMeanwhile, the Vulture reads a newspaper in his hideout -- an abandoned silo in Staten Island -- and learns that some diamonds are about to be moved by a jewelry exchange.&nbsp; He is so confident that he'll be able to get his hands on the shipment that he flies directly off toward Manhattan and throws notes through the windows of three buildings (Jameson Publishing Company, the radio network, and the office of the police chief).&nbsp; All declare his intent to \"steal the diamond shipment from under your noses!\"\n\nBut he's spotted by Spider-Man, who is attempting to get close enough to snap some photos (hoping to make a \"small fortune\").&nbsp; The Vulture notices this and attacks the unsuspecting hero, depositing him in nearby water tower, before flying off.&nbsp; But even though Spider-Man has forgotten to refill his web fluid, and the walls of the tower are too wet and slimy for him to crawl upward on the walls, he uses his great strength to leap upward and eventually escape.\n\nRetrieving the camera that was knocked out of his hands during the Vulture's attack, he takes it home and develops the photos, which turn out to be great, but whom should he sell them to?&nbsp; Deciding it would be a great joke to offer them to the Spider-Man-hating publisher of <i>Now</i> magazine, he decides on Jameson himself, who will never know that he's actually helping his number one target.\n\nBut in the meantime, the brief encounter with the Vulture has revealed some deficiencies in his outfit, which Peter had originally designed only to be colorful, meant to help him make money as an entertainer.&nbsp; But if he's to continue his adventures as Spider-Man, he realizes it needs an upgrade, with the primary addition of spare web-fluid being number one on his list.&nbsp; He should never again find himself without spiderlike webbing, and he finds room on his belt for a miniature camera as well.&nbsp; Once the upgrades are finished, he turns to the problem of the Vulture, believing he's figured out how the Vulture is able to fly... and works on a device in preparation of their next encounter.\n\nThe next day, Peter contacts Jameson to let him know that he has dramatic photos of the Vulture, which he agrees to sell to the publisher on the condition that he never ask <i>how</i> he got them, even insisting that his <i>name</i> never be mentioned as photographer.\n\nSoon, the jewelry exchange commences with everyone watching (thanks to the prior notice he provided), all guarded by police and a helicopter.&nbsp; Surely, the Vulture would be <i>insane</i> to attempt a heist this well guarded!&nbsp; But while everyone searches the skies <i>above</i>, the Vulture suddenly appears from <i>under</i> a manhole and disappears with the loot, emerging far away through the subway entrance.\n\nBut Spider-Man has already scaled the wall of a tall building, which allows him to spot the soaring Vulture, who is on his way back to his secret hideout.&nbsp; Able to stay on his tail with the help of his webbing, the two eventually meet, and once Spider-Man snags the Vulture's leg in mid-air, he activates his new device, and the Vulture finds he can't stay aloft.\n\nPeter swings down to a nearby roof to snap photos of the police arresting the Vulture, who has been forced to spiral downward, right into the hands of the waiting police.&nbsp; He had deduced that the absence of noise in the Vulture's flight was the clue he needed to figure out the wings operated using magnetic power, so he whipped up an \"anti-magnetic inverter\" to counteract it.\n\nHe sells the photos to Jameson, enough to pay the rent for a full year and tells Aunt May \"Tomorrow, I'm buying you the newest kitchen appliances you ever drooled over!\"&nbsp; May is proud and indicates that he's \"the most wonderful boy in the world!\"\n\nThe story ends with Vulture, in prison, swearing his revenge on Spider-Man!",
  "grade_one_liner": "A lively half‑issue built on character and problem‑solving, with a villain who does just enough.&nbsp; The momentum and craft carry the day more than the menace does.",
  "subtitle": "When Craft Outweighs Page Count",
  "review_text": "[SPAN: severity=info; fonttype=bold; text=FOR THE RECORD:]\n[BR] This is a review of the <b>first</b> of the two stories found in this magazine.\n[BR] My review on the other story is posted elsewhere.\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[ASSET: right | VultureCloseup | width=16%] A strong and confident early adventure, introducing a new and different antagonist for the title hero, and right off the bat, artist Steve Ditko does a great job showing off the new \"Vulture\" (with this close-up on his face being one of the highlight panels).\n[BR]\n[BR] Ditko's design sense is already doing heavy lifting here -- the Vulture's gaunt, almost skeletal face fits right into Ditko's gallery of unsettling figures.\n\nEven in a story that isn't perfect, he absolutely <i>nails</i> the character's visual identity -- a balding man, easily middle-aged (or even older), who confidently predicts that \"even Spider-Man\" won't be able to stop him!&nbsp; (It's interesting that, as early as the book's second issue, crooks such as him are already including Spider-Man as part of their mental calculus.)\n\nBut even if one sets aside the new villain, think of all the plot elements that are introduced in this one half-length story alone:\n[HANG] * Peter Parker is established as one with photographic skills (or at least has aspirations in the field)\n[HANG] * We drop in on Peter's activities at school and his brief interactions with Aunt May\n[HANG] * Spider-Man must remember to refill his web fluid (we're shown he forgot to do this on page 6)\n[HANG] * He is introduced to <i>Now</i> publisher J. Jonah Jameson and arranges a covert way to make money\n[HANG] * We get a quick peek into how he upgrades his costume to hold extra web cartridges and a miniature camera\n[HANG] * And finally, we see how Peter uses his brain to ultimately defeat the Vulture, in addition to his muscles and spider-powers, of course.\n\nThat level of layering is seems unusually ambitious for <i>any</i> character in only 14 pages, and it goes to show how seriously this magazine seems to be taken by Marvel, especially when put up next to some of its other features, such as Ant-Man over in <i>Tales to Astonish</i>, and even Thor over in <i>Journey Into Mystery</i>.\n\nAlready, we see signs that this \"Spider-Man\" is not only <i>different</i>, but that the co-creators Lee and Ditko seem to be trying harder than most of the company's early‑'60s output.&nbsp; Peter is being treated as a character with far more of a life that the others, complete with obligations, not to mention consequences.&nbsp; It's this emotional grounding that helps elevate the subject matter.&nbsp; Peter's personal struggles give the story a sense of weight that the other features only seem to <i>gesture</i> toward.\n\n[ASSET: left | CostumeUpgrades | width=18%] The fact that Peter instantly realizes how his Spider-Man uniform has glaring deficiencies was simply <i>brilliant</i>.\n[BR]\n[BR] I have already commented that I very much like how the new Iron Man character tinkers with his armor over in <i>Tales of Suspense</i>, and as a reader, you get the impression that sort of fiddling seems likely to be part of his whole shtick.&nbsp; But in <i>this</i> case, Peter's upgrades feel much more like a one-time thing, and that may well be the case.\n[BR]\n[BR] Even so, the brainy teenager is forced to face the fact that the colorful costume he originally designed to draw a crowd for entertainment purposes now needs to be more serviceable if he's going to be swinging around town as a costumed adventurer.&nbsp; That's a somber analysis of his situation as a public figure, and once again goes to show how this magazine feels more vibrant than most of it contemporaries.\n\nIt also reinforces a key aspect of Spider‑Man's identity:&nbsp; he's not just agile and strong -- he's a problem‑solver, and so his gear evolves because <i>he</i> evolves.&nbsp; (Just go back to my [LINK:1962:JIM_83_thor0|JIM #83] review for a comparison - there is no \"Asgardian instruction booklet\" here -- Peter is alone and is making it all up as he goes.)\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[ASSET: right | AsForTheVulture | width=8%] And the co-creators don't even stop there.&nbsp; Once Peter has fashioned places on his belt to hold extra web cartridges and his camera (apparently a new miniature one that he plans to fit in his belt after getting paid by Jameson), he immediately shifts to the much more immediate threat of the Vulture, putting his mind to work on how his artificial wings function.\n\n[ASSET: left | PeterSneaksAway | width=16%] But even as Peter seems to have found a solution to some of the money problems we saw in the first issue, page 8 shows him to be as unpopular at school as ever, and when he finally excuses himself from the onlooking crowd on page 9, his exit is called out by Flash Thompson (who was given a name on page 2 of <i>Amazing Fantasy </i>#15).\n[BR]\n[BR] As a reader, you <i>already</i> want to punch this guy in the face!&nbsp; (<i>Heh</i>)\n\nMoments like this remind the reader that Peter's victories as Spider‑Man don't translate into victories as Peter Parker.&nbsp; This kind of everyday humiliation helps keep the Spider-Man heroics from floating too far above the ground, not to mention drawing readers back for the next adventure.\n\n[ASSET: right | AttackFromBelow | width=9%] The Vulture's audacity at first <i>announcing</i> his intention to steal the diamonds and then pulling off the heist, quite <i>literally</i> \"under your noses\" (as advertised in his note) was indeed well done by the co-creators, and I imagine no reader ever suspected that he might accomplish the theft in this manner.\n\n[ASSET: left | Captured | width=11%] It was a clever move, but of course, the Vulture never reckoned on Spider-Man escaping the water tower, and the two inevitably meet for a final \"battle\" (in which not a single punch was thrown).&nbsp; Instead, the Vulture's magnetically-powered wings are thwarted by a brainy teenager, who sends him ultimately into a tailspin and is able to capture photos for Jameson.\n\nIt was a confrontation built on setup and payoff, solved through <i>deduction</i> rather than brute force (perhaps rare for superhero comics of the time), which gives it a satisfying internal logic and help hints that Spider‑Man stories in particular might actually hinge on Peter's cleverness rather than Spider-Man's raw power.\n\n\n[BOTTOM_LINE]\nIt's almost astonishing all of the above was able to be done in <b>just the first half of a single issue</b>, so nothing at all to sneeze at!&nbsp; Very impressive, in fact!\n\nThe Vulture is a new character, but his introduction in this story was well-done, with Ditko's art seeming perfectly suited to illustrate the bizarre motions of both he and the costumed web-slinger (page 12 expertly demonstrates the mid-air flailing of limbs), so an <i>excellent </i>job all around in the art department.\n\nAnd from a story perspective, as early as the first panel on page 2, it's established that the Vulture's flight is completely silent, and the fact that his wings are artificial is also mentioned on page 4.&nbsp; That page also reinforces how they make no sound, which ends up being the clue Peter uses in the end to deduce how to counteract them.\n\nAdmittedly, that may have been a mite too insightful for a mere teenager to come up with, but I think the overriding point is clear -- Peter Parker isn't any <i>normal</i> teenager.&nbsp; He's intelligent, and this story seems bound and determined to completely lean into that aspect of the character.\n\nIn some sense, it seems more important than even his spiderlike powers.&nbsp; Peter is a youth who tinkers, experiments, and tries to reason his way through problems even when the situation seems wildly beyond what any teenager should reasonably be able to handle.&nbsp; The deduction may come quickly, but it's consistent with how he appears to approach challenges.\n\nIf the story does one thing wrong, it's that it leaves the reader with the impression that all the Parker money troubles have been solved at the end, and that seems to fly in the face of the dire circumstances we were shown just one issue earlier.&nbsp; The contrast is <i>sharp</i> because that first issue leaned so heavily on financial strain as a defining pressure in their lives.\n\n[ASSET: right | GetYouNextTime | width=15%] Finally, no review of this story should end without some sort of chuckle over its final panel, which shows the Vulture standing in his prison cell, still in full Vulture attire, which is, of course, <i>absurd</i>, and yet it seems symptomatic of comic book storytelling of the day.\n[BR]\n[BR] The whole \"Curse you, Spider-Man!&nbsp; I'll get you <i>next</i> time!\" trope plays as funny, which is why I won't penalize it too much.\n\nThere's also something wonderfully theatrical about it -- as if Marvel doesn't want the Vulture to break character even when he's behind bars.\n\nSilly?&nbsp; <i>Of course!</i>\n[BR] But it's exactly the kind of <i>earnestness</i> that gives these early stories their charm.\n\nIt was <i>not</i> a perfect story, but it did more than enough to keep the readers invested, adding a new villain, reminding us of Peter's situation at home, and featuring just about all the supporting cast, all within the space of one half of a book.&nbsp; You have no choice but to tip your cap in admiration, even if the story's new antagonist doesn't seem capable of ever elevating to one of Spider-Man's greatest villains.\n\nTaken together, the issue shows how much can be packed into a short feature when the creators focus on character, problem‑solving, and a villain with a clear hook.&nbsp; It's a compact but energetic piece of storytelling that stands out among its contemporaries.\n\nIt's the sort of story that on first reading, feels lightweight, but rewards closer inspection, because the craft is <i>right there</i> on the page -- earnest, energetic, and demonstrating that the creators were heavily invested in making this succeed.",
  "side_note": [
    "The first panel on page 4 reveals the Vulture's hideout in an \"abandoned silo in Staten Island,\" but also misspells Manhattan, as shown here (<i>oops</i>):\n[ASSET: center | Manhatten | width=medium]"
